By brute-force scanning. In the test's `setUp()`, the `_scanForAgentIds()` function iterates through agent IDs 0 to 1000 and calls `registry.getAgentWallet(i)` on the real on-chain Self Agent Registry for each one, comparing the returned wallet address against the two target addresses:

```solidity
function _scanForAgentIds() internal {
    for (uint256 i = 0; i <= SCAN_MAX; i++) {
        try registry.getAgentWallet(i) returns (address wallet) {
            if (wallet == ADDR_1 && !addr1Found) {
                addr1AgentId = i;   // <-- found it at i=50
                addr1Found = true;
            }
            if (wallet == ADDR_2 && !addr2Found) {
                addr2AgentId = i;
                addr2Found = true;
            }
            if (addr1Found && addr2Found) break;
        } catch {
            // Agent ID doesn't exist or reverts, continue
        }
    }
}
```

At `i = 50`, `registry.getAgentWallet(50)` returned `0x31493cA48BC88f0Ee2Ecd96f4D87251046825d65`, which matched `ADDR_1`. That's how it was discovered.

There's no reverse lookup function like `getAgentIdByWallet(address)` on the registry, so scanning sequentially was the only option. The `SCAN_MAX = 1000` cap is arbitrary -- if the agent ID were higher than 1000, it would have been missed. For address 2, nothing matched in that range.

Yes, exactly. The test deploys your actual `AgentMicrolending` contract on the Celo fork, pointing it at the real registry:

```solidity
lending = new AgentMicrolending(CELO_USDC, SELF_REGISTRY);
```

Then when we impersonate address 1 and call `createLoanRequest`, your contract's `onlyVerifiedAgent` modifier runs against the real on-chain state:

```solidity
modifier onlyVerifiedAgent(uint256 agentId) {
    if (selfRegistry.getAgentWallet(agentId) != msg.sender) revert NotVerifiedAgent();
    if (!selfRegistry.hasHumanProof(agentId)) revert NotVerifiedAgent();
    _;
}
```

For address 1 with `agentId = 50`:
1. `selfRegistry.getAgentWallet(50)` returns `0x31493c...` which equals `msg.sender` -- passes
2. `selfRegistry.hasHumanProof(50)` returns `true` -- passes
3. Loan created successfully

For address 2 with `agentId = 0` (or any ID):
1. `selfRegistry.getAgentWallet(0)` does NOT return `0x1358...` -- reverts with `NotVerifiedAgent`

So yes, the on-chain check in your contract works correctly. A human delegated their identity to address 1 via the Self registry, and your modifier enforces that only that verified agent can borrow. Address 2 has no delegation and gets blocked.

